Please try again later.Mark B.2.0 out of 5 stars Inconvenient Measurements & Designs: Consider Before Purchase Reviewed in the United States on July 4, 2018Verified Purchase Consider this before buying: The inside of the ear cup is 7/16" deep, 1 9/16" wide, and 2 5/8" tall. The BIG, BULKY CORD weighs close to 4 ounces by itself—that's around 30% of the total combined weight of the headset and cord (the headset only weighs around or a little over 9 ounces). The volume has to be significantly loud, maybe too loud, to hear over an acoustic drum set.I haven't seen a survey on the average ear size of the U.S. population, but chances are that this design does NOT accommodate a lot of people. For me, the cup touches all sides of my outer ear, and the inner screen presses against the surface of my ear, and the foam cushion barely touches my head where it's supposed to. This is not my idea of a comfortable fit.The BIG, BULKY CORD yanks down on the ear cup it is attached to (left) if it dangles free, and it easily displaces the ear cup if it is allowed to swing around, such as when your body is turning/twisting to reach parts of the drum set; fastening it to your shirt or waist band helps, but the stiffness of the cord then causes the cup to displace if you turn your head from side to side. It is a menacing annoyance down the front of the body because it so easily gets in the way there, and running down the back results in a constant backward pull on the earcup, there again often displacing the ear cup.The ambient sound dampening is just enough to save the eardrums from the sharp sound bursts of drum and cymbal attacks, but the music being played to has to be turned up so loud in order to be heard over an acoustic drum set in play that any hearing-saving qualities get compromised again. As for the sound quality, I'm not as critical as others. The quality is at least as good as a standard set of earphones or earbuds, and I am able to hear the parts of the music that I need to hear for keeping time and playing along—if turned up loud enough (uncomfortably loud).This sounds like a one-star rating, but I gave it a second star because they are not completely useless. They work, very basically, for the drums if one can get beyond the inconveniences, and maybe more as a last resort for whatever qualities they offer. Overall, I wish I had simply spent the money on a decent pair of headphones that are actually designed to meet the needs of drummers, rather than hoping to get lucky on an economy-priced headset like this. Read more 3 people found this helpful Helpful Report abuse Kyle3.0 out of 5 stars Sound like garbage, uncomfortable, not a great seal Reviewed in the United States on January 3, 2020Verified Purchase I'm not much a fan of these isolation cans. Having used the Vic Firth isolation headphones for drumming a great deal, I prefer the comfort and sound of those units-- even though the Vic Firths don't sound great either. Comparatively, the CADs are less comfortable and do not seal on the ear as well, so they do not isolate as nicely.All that being said, the CADs have held up much longer than the Vic Firths. So, if durability is key, go for the CADs. I still use them, sometimes isolation is just more important that comfort or quality. Read more 2 people found this helpful Helpful Report abuse Daniel Richmond2.0 out of 5 stars Wish I would have spent just a little more on a better item Reviewed in the United States on January 13, 2016Verified Purchase I had initially given these a 5/5 due to their isolation and seemingly just the fact that they produced sound, but after a couple years I've become quite disappointed with them.I use these almost exclusively for recording drums. That means I need to be able to hear the rest of the mix, my own monitored playing, and -- most importantly -- a clear click track that I can easily lock in on for time-keeping.These do block out the majority of my kit's volume, which is essential, but the sound quality is SO muddled, distorts SO easily, and is lacking SO MUCH high-end that just trying to separate the click from the rest of the track requires a ton of concentration. Listening should be natural so I can concentrate on playing, and it just isn't with these.That said, after a couple years of semi-regularly blowing recordings on account of not being able to hear what's going on, I'm finally going to count my losses and spend just a bit more on a better set of cans. Read more Helpful Report abuse Apryl Kisandria Varga5.0 out of 5 stars Excellent headphones for noise Cancellation Reviewed in the United States on August 5, 2013Verified Purchase My brother is a drummer. I am not. I write for a living, but in a very Google-esque, incubator type-office. I have been encountering a lot of difficulty concentrating at work due to all the noise around me, so my brother recommended these headphones. I still cannot believe they were under $40. They work so well, even without music playing in the background.Although I'm sure they work excellently for drummers, if you work in a loud office, or other loud environment and are looking for some great headphones that cancel out 99% of the noise around you, these are perfect! Reviewed in the United Kingdom on February 24, 2015Verified Purchase The first pair I got were broken.Amazon were quick to issue me with a replacement, but it shook my faith in the company a little to think that their products are sent out untested. The second pair I recieved work well and cancel the noise of my kit well. They make is easy to learn songs play along with intricate things such a ghost notes without drowning them out. As with most noise-isolating 'over the ear' headphones, they do pinch my head and sweat my ears after a while, but I far prefer that to them sliding about and allowing too much sound in. My concern for the future is that the metal fastening the over'head strap to the actual speakers seems quite flimsy and I can see the fit deteriorating over time. Please try again later.Mark B.2.0 out of 5 stars Inconvenient Measurements & Designs: Consider Before Purchase Reviewed in the United States on July 4, 2018Verified Purchase Consider this before buying: The inside of the ear cup is 7/16" deep, 1 9/16" wide, and 2 5/8" tall. The BIG, BULKY CORD weighs close to 4 ounces by itself—that's around 30% of the total combined weight of the headset and cord (the headset only weighs around or a little over 9 ounces). The volume has to be significantly loud, maybe too loud, to hear over an acoustic drum set.I haven't seen a survey on the average ear size of the U.S. population, but chances are that this design does NOT accommodate a lot of people. For me, the cup touches all sides of my outer ear, and the inner screen presses against the surface of my ear, and the foam cushion barely touches my head where it's supposed to. This is not my idea of a comfortable fit.The BIG, BULKY CORD yanks down on the ear cup it is attached to (left) if it dangles free, and it easily displaces the ear cup if it is allowed to swing around, such as when your body is turning/twisting to reach parts of the drum set; fastening it to your shirt or waist band helps, but the stiffness of the cord then causes the cup to displace if you turn your head from side to side. It is a menacing annoyance down the front of the body because it so easily gets in the way there, and running down the back results in a constant backward pull on the earcup, there again often displacing the ear cup.The ambient sound dampening is just enough to save the eardrums from the sharp sound bursts of drum and cymbal attacks, but the music being played to has to be turned up so loud in order to be heard over an acoustic drum set in play that any hearing-saving qualities get compromised again. As for the sound quality, I'm not as critical as others. The quality is at least as good as a standard set of earphones or earbuds, and I am able to hear the parts of the music that I need to hear for keeping time and playing along—if turned up loud enough (uncomfortably loud).This sounds like a one-star rating, but I gave it a second star because they are not completely useless. They work, very basically, for the drums if one can get beyond the inconveniences, and maybe more as a last resort for whatever qualities they offer. Overall, I wish I had simply spent the money on a decent pair of headphones that are actually designed to meet the needs of drummers, rather than hoping to get lucky on an economy-priced headset like this. The volume has to be significantly loud, maybe too loud, to hear over an acoustic drum set.I haven't seen a survey on the average ear size of the U.S. population, but chances are that this design does NOT accommodate a lot of people. For me, the cup touches all sides of my outer ear, and the inner screen presses against the surface of my ear, and the foam cushion barely touches my head where it's supposed to. This is not my idea of a comfortable fit.The BIG, BULKY CORD yanks down on the ear cup it is attached to (left) if it dangles free, and it easily displaces the ear cup if it is allowed to swing around, such as when your body is turning/twisting to reach parts of the drum set; fastening it to your shirt or waist band helps, but the stiffness of the cord then causes the cup to displace if you turn your head from side to side. It is a menacing annoyance down the front of the body because it so easily gets in the way there, and running down the back results in a constant backward pull on the earcup, there again often displacing the ear cup.The ambient sound dampening is just enough to save the eardrums from the sharp sound bursts of drum and cymbal attacks, but the music being played to has to be turned up so loud in order to be heard over an acoustic drum set in play that any hearing-saving qualities get compromised again. As for the sound quality, I'm not as critical as others. The quality is at least as good as a standard set of earphones or earbuds, and I am able to hear the parts of the music that I need to hear for keeping time and playing along—if turned up loud enough (uncomfortably loud).This sounds like a one-star rating, but I gave it a second star because they are not completely useless. They work, very basically, for the drums if one can get beyond the inconveniences, and maybe more as a last resort for whatever qualities they offer. Overall, I wish I had simply spent the money on a decent pair of headphones that are actually designed to meet the needs of drummers, rather than hoping to get lucky on an economy-priced headset like this.

Daniel Richmond2.0 out of 5 stars Wish I would have spent just a little more on a better item Reviewed in the United States on January 13, 2016Verified Purchase I had initially given these a 5/5 due to their isolation and seemingly just the fact that they produced sound, but after a couple years I've become quite disappointed with them.I use these almost exclusively for recording drums. That means I need to be able to hear the rest of the mix, my own monitored playing, and -- most importantly -- a clear click track that I can easily lock in on for time-keeping.These do block out the majority of my kit's volume, which is essential, but the sound quality is SO muddled, distorts SO easily, and is lacking SO MUCH high-end that just trying to separate the click from the rest of the track requires a ton of concentration. Listening should be natural so I can concentrate on playing, and it just isn't with these.That said, after a couple years of semi-regularly blowing recordings on account of not being able to hear what's going on, I'm finally going to count my losses and spend just a bit more on a better set of cans.
